window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>1>a>i","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : CLASSIFICATION OF TAX","question":"The graph below shows the imposition of tax on the sellers of a product. Study the graph and answer the questions that follow.    Identify    price per unit of the product before tax","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The price per unit of the product before the tax is imposed is represented by the equilibrium price at the original supply curve (S\u2080) and the demand curve (D).    In the graph:  The original equilibrium point is where S\u2080 intersects with D.  At this point, the price per unit is $80.    Thus, the price per unit of the product before the tax is $80.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>1>a>ii","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : CLASSIFICATION OF TAX","question":"The graph below shows the imposition of tax on the sellers of a product. Study the graph and answer the questions that follow.    Identify  quantity demanded and supplied before tax","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The quantity demanded and supplied before the tax is imposed is represented by the original equilibrium point, where the original supply curve (S\u2080) intersects with the demand curve (D).    In the graph:  The original equilibrium occurs at the intersection of S\u2080 and D.  At this intersection, the quantity is 54 units.  Thus, the quantity demanded and supplied before the tax is 54 units.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>1>a>iii","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : CLASSIFICATION OF TAX","question":"The graph below shows the imposition of tax on the sellers of a product. Study the graph and answer the questions that follow.    Identify  price per unit of the product after tax","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The price per unit of the product after the tax is imposed is determined by the new equilibrium point where the new supply curve (S\u2081) intersects with the demand curve (D).    In the graph:  After the tax is imposed, the supply curve shifts from S\u2080 to S\u2081.  The new equilibrium occurs at the intersection of S\u2081 and D.  At this point, the price per unit is $100.    Thus, the price per unit of the product after the tax is $100.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>1>a>iv","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iv","group":"","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : CLASSIFICATION OF TAX","question":"The graph below shows the imposition of tax on the sellers of a product. Study the graph and answer the questions that follow.    Identify  quantity demanded and supplied after tax","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The quantity demanded and supplied after the tax is imposed is determined by the new equilibrium point where the new supply curve (S\u2081) intersects with the demand curve (D).    In the graph:  After the tax is imposed, the supply curve shifts from S\u2080 to S\u2081.  The new equilibrium occurs at the intersection of S\u2081 and D.  At this intersection, the quantity is 54 units.    Thus, the quantity demanded and supplied after the tax is 54 units.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>1>b>i","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : ELASTICITY OF TAX~~PUBLIC FINANCE : PRINCIPLE OF TAXATION","question":"The graph below shows the imposition of tax on the sellers of a product. Study the graph and answer the questions that follow.    Identify  Determine the amount of tax imposed per unit of the product","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The amount of tax imposed per unit of the product is calculated as the vertical distance between the original supply curve (S\u2080) and the new supply curve (S\u2081) at the new equilibrium quantity.    In the graph:  Before the tax, the equilibrium price was $80 (where S\u2080 intersects D).  After the tax, the price paid by consumers is $100 (where S\u2081 intersects D).  The sellers receive $75 per unit after the tax (where S\u2080 intersects the new quantity of 54 units).  The tax per unit is the difference between the price consumers pay ($100) and the price sellers receive ($75):    Tax per unit = $100 - $75 = $25","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>1>b>ii","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : ELASTICITY OF TAX","question":"The graph below shows the imposition of tax on the sellers of a product. Study the graph and answer the questions that follow.    Identify  Determine the amount retained per unit by the seller after tax","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The amount retained per unit by the seller after the tax is imposed is determined by the price at which the original supply curve (S\u2080) intersects the quantity sold after the tax.    In the graph:  After the tax, the new equilibrium price is $100, which consumers pay.  The original supply curve (S\u2080) intersects the new quantity sold (54 units) at a price of $75.  This $75 is the amount retained by the seller per unit after the tax, as the difference between $100 and $75 ($25) represents the tax.    Thus, the amount retained per unit by the seller after the tax is $75.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>1>c>i","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : ELASTICITY OF TAX","question":"The graph below shows the imposition of tax on the sellers of a product. Study the graph and answer the questions that follow.    Identify  Calculate the percentage of the total tax imposed that is paid by buyers per unit","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Identify the total tax per unit:  The total tax per unit is $25 (as calculated earlier).  Calculate the portion of the tax paid by buyers:    Before the tax, the price was $80.  After the tax, the price buyers pay is $100.  The portion of the tax paid by buyers is $100 - $80 = $20.    Calculate the percentage of the total tax paid by buyers:  Percentage = (Portion paid by buyers / Total tax) \u00d7 100  Percentage = ($20 / $25) \u00d7 100 = 80%    Thus, 80% of the total tax imposed is paid by buyers per unit.","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>1>c>ii","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : ELASTICITY OF TAX","question":"The graph below shows the imposition of tax on the sellers of a product. Study the graph and answer the questions that follow.    Identify  Calculate the percentage of the total tax imposed that is paid by sellers per unit","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Identify the total tax per unit:    The total tax per unit is $25 (as calculated earlier).    Calculate the portion of the tax paid by sellers:  Before the tax, the price was $80.  After the tax, the amount sellers receive is $75.  The portion of the tax paid by sellers is $80 - $75 = $5.    Calculate the percentage of the total tax paid by sellers:  Percentage = (Portion paid by sellers / Total tax) \u00d7 100  Percentage = ($5 / $25) \u00d7 100 = 20%    Thus, 20% of the total tax imposed is paid by sellers per unit.","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>2>a>i","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"THE THEORY OF DEMAND : ELASTICITY OF DEMAND","question":"The management of fruit juice production company was directed by the shareholders to increase the revenue from the sale of its product. The management decided to increase the price of the fruit juice from $7 to $10 per unit and this led to a fall in quantity demanded from 150 units to 30 units.     Use the information above to answer the questions that follow:    percentage increase in the price","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Given:  Old Price = $7  New Price = $10    Percentageincrease=New price -Old priceOld pricex100  =10 - 77x100    =37x100  = 42.86%.","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>2>a>ii","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"THE THEORY OF DEMAND : ELASTICITY OF DEMAND","question":"The management of fruit juice production company was directed by the shareholders to increase the revenue from the sale of its product. The management decided to increase the price of the fruit juice from $7 to $10 per unit and this led to a fall in quantity demanded from 150 units to 30 units.     Use the information above to answer the questions that follow:    percentage decrease in the quantity demanded","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Given:  Old Quantity = 150 units  New Quantity = 30 units    = 30- 150 150x100    =- 120150x100  = - 80%.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>2>a>iii","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"","topic":"THE THEORY OF DEMAND : ELASTICITY OF DEMAND","question":"The management of fruit juice production company was directed by the shareholders to increase the revenue from the sale of its product. The management decided to increase the price of the fruit juice from $7 to $10 per unit and this led to a fall in quantity demanded from 150 units to 30 units.     Use the information above to answer the questions that follow:    coefficient of price elasticity of demand for the fruit juice","images":[],"marking_scheme":"=Percentage change in the quantity demanededPercentage change in the price  PED=\u221280%42.86%\u200b   \u2248\u22121.87  ignore the negative sign, therefore: e = 1.87","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>2>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"THE THEORY OF DEMAND : ELASTICITY OF DEMAND","question":"The management of fruit juice production company was directed by the shareholders to increase the revenue from the sale of its product. The management decided to increase the price of the fruit juice from $7 to $10 per unit and this led to a fall in quantity demanded from 150 units to 30 units.     Use the information above to answer the questions that follow:    Is the demand for the fruit juice, price elastic or inelastic? Give a reason for your answer.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The demand for the fruit juice is price elastic.    Reason:  Since the absolute value of PED 1.87 is greater than 1, it indicates that the demand is elastic. This means that the percentage change in quantity demanded is greater than the percentage change in price. In other words, the quantity demanded is highly responsive to changes in price.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>2>c","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"","topic":"THE CONCEPT OF COST & REVENUE : APPLICATION OF ELASTICITY ON REVENUE","question":"The management of fruit juice production company was directed by the shareholders to increase the revenue from the sale of its product. The management decided to increase the price of the fruit juice from $7 to $10 per unit and this led to a fall in quantity demanded from 150 units to 30 units.     Use the information above to answer the questions that follow:    Did the management of the company achieve its objective of increasing revenue?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"To determine if revenue increased, calculate the total revenue before and after the price change.  Initial Revenue:  Initial Revenue = Old Price \u00d7 Old Quantity   Initial Revenue = 7 \u00d7 150  = $1050    \tNew Revenue:  New Revenue = New Price \u00d7 New Quantity  New Revenue =10 \u00d7 30  = $300    Since the initial revenue was $1050 and the new revenue is $300, the revenue decreased significantly. This decrease is due to the substantial drop in quantity demanded, which outweighed the increase in price. Thus, the management's objective to increase revenue was not achieved.","marks":"6","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>2>d","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"d","group":"","topic":"THE CONCEPT OF COST & REVENUE : APPLICATION OF ELASTICITY ON REVENUE","question":"The management of fruit juice production company was directed by the shareholders to increase the revenue from the sale of its product. The management decided to increase the price of the fruit juice from $7 to $10 per unit and this led to a fall in quantity demanded from 150 units to 30 units.     Use the information above to answer the questions that follow:    From your answers in 2(a)(iii), was the increase in the price of the price of the fruit juice a rational strategy to employ in order to increase revenue? Explain your answer.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"No, increasing the price of the fruit juice was not a rational strategy to increase revenue.    Explanation:  Based on the previous calculation, the price elasticity of demand (PED) for the fruit juice was approximately 1.87, indicating that the demand is elastic. When demand is elastic, the percentage change in quantity demanded is greater than the percentage change in price. As a result, a price increase leads to a proportionally larger decrease in quantity demanded, which causes a reduction in total revenue.    In this case:  Initial Revenue: $1050  New Revenue: $300    The significant drop in quantity demanded (from 150 units to 30 units) due to the price increase (from $7 to $10) resulted in a substantial decrease in revenue. Therefore, increasing the price was not a rational strategy for increasing revenue because it led to a decrease rather than an increase in total revenue.","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>3>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"THEORY OF SUPPLY : DISTINCTION BETWEEN CHANGE IN QUANTITY SUPPLIED AND CHANGE IN SUPPLY","question":"With the aid of relevant diagrams, distinguish between an increase in supply and an increase in quantity supplied","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Increase in Supply:        In this diagram above, the supply curve shifts from S to S1, indicating an increase in supply. This shift to the right means that producers are willing to supply more of the product at each price level. The equilibrium price decreases from P to P1, and the equilibrium quantity increases from Q to Q1.    Increase in Quantity Supplied:      In this diagram, the supply curve remains unchanged (S), but the quantity supplied increases, moving along the supply curve from the initial equilibrium point to a new point on the supply curve. This means that producers are willing to supply more of the product at the same price level, without a shift in the supply curve.    The key difference is that an increase in supply refers to a rightward shift of the supply curve, indicating a change in the underlying factors that affect supply, such as technology, input prices, or the number of producers. In contrast, an increase in quantity supplied refers to a movement along the same supply curve, indicating a change in the quantity supplied in response to a change in price, without a shift in the supply curve.","marks":"12","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>3>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : INTRODUCTION","question":"Explain how a decrease in income tax will affect the demand for a normal good and an inferior good","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Normal Good:  A normal good is one for which demand increases as consumer income rises.    Effect of Decrease in Income Tax:  Increased Disposable Income: A decrease in income tax leaves consumers with more disposable income.  Higher Demand: With more disposable income, consumers are likely to increase their demand for normal goods because they can now afford to buy more of these items.  Shifts in Demand Curve: This increased demand will shift the demand curve for normal goods to the right, indicating a higher quantity demanded at each price level.    Inferior Good:  An inferior good is one for which demand decreases as consumer income rises.    Effect of Decrease in Income Tax:  Increased Disposable Income: Similar to normal goods, a decrease in income tax increases consumers' disposable income.  Lower Demand: As consumers' income increases, they are likely to reduce their demand for inferior goods. This is because they can now afford to substitute inferior goods with higher-quality alternatives (normal or superior goods).  Shifts in Demand Curve: This decrease in demand will shift the demand curve for inferior goods to the left, indicating a lower quantity demanded at each price level.","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>3>c","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"","topic":"THEORY OF SUPPLY : MEANING AND DETERMINANTS","question":"Explain how an increase in the supply of a substitute will affect the demand for a commodity","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Substitutes are goods that can replace each other in consumption. When the price or availability of one substitute changes, it impacts the demand for the other.    Increase in Supply of a Substitute:  When the supply of a substitute increases, several key effects unfold:    Decrease in Price of the Substitute:  An increase in supply generally leads to a decrease in the price of the substitute due to the higher availability of the product.    Substitution Effect:  Consumers, motivated by the lower price of the substitute, may choose to buy more of it instead of the original commodity. This is known as the substitution effect.    Decrease in Demand for the Original Commodity:  As consumers switch to the cheaper substitute, the demand for the original commodity decreases. This happens because the original commodity is now relatively more expensive or less attractive compared to the increased supply and reduced price of the substitute.    Shift in the Demand Curve:  The demand curve for the original commodity shifts to the left. This leftward shift indicates that, at every price level, the quantity demanded for the original commodity has decreased.  Example:  Consider two substitute goods: butter and margarine. If the supply of margarine increases significantly, leading to a decrease in its price, consumers who previously bought butter might start buying more margarine due to its lower price. Consequently, the demand for butter would decrease, resulting in a leftward shift in the butter demand curve.","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>4>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"DISTRIBUTIVE TRADE : INTRODUCTION","question":"Define the term distribution","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Distribution refers to the process and activities involved in moving goods or services from the producer to the final consumer. It encompasses the entire chain of steps and intermediaries that a product passes through, including transportation, warehousing, and logistics, as well as the marketing and selling strategies employed to reach customers effectively.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>4>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"DISTRIBUTIVE TRADE : THE RETAILER","question":"Outline three ways in which the retailer is important to the consumer","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Wide Product Availability: Retailers provide a wide range of products in one location, making it convenient for consumers to find and purchase what they need without having to visit multiple stores.    Convenient Locations: Retailers are often located in accessible areas such as shopping malls, neighborhood stores, and online platforms, making it easy for consumers to shop at their convenience.    Product Knowledge and Advice: Retailers offer valuable product information and recommendations, helping consumers make informed purchasing decisions. Sales associates can provide guidance based on consumer needs and preferences.    After-Sales Support: Retailers often provide services such as returns, exchanges, warranties, and repairs, enhancing the overall shopping experience and ensuring customer satisfaction.    Diverse Product Selection: Retailers typically stock a variety of brands, models, and product types, giving consumers a wide selection to choose from based on their preferences, budget, and specific requirements.    Promotions and Discounts: Retailers frequently offer promotions, discounts, and special deals, allowing consumers to benefit from competitive prices and cost savings on their purchases.","marks":"9","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>4>c","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"","topic":"DISTRIBUTIVE TRADE : THE MIDDLEMEN","question":"Explain three disadvantages of the operations of middlemen in the distribution process","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Middlemen, or intermediaries, play a significant role in the distribution process by connecting producers with consumers. However, their involvement can introduce several disadvantages:    Higher Prices for Consumers: Middlemen add their own margins to the price of goods to cover their costs and make a profit. This often results in higher prices for the final consumers as each intermediary adds a markup to the product's cost.    Reduced Profits for Producers: Producers may receive less for their products as a portion of the sales revenue goes to intermediaries. This can reduce the overall profitability for the producers.    Delays in Distribution: Each intermediary in the distribution chain can introduce delays. The more intermediaries there are, the longer it may take for products to reach the final consumer.    Complex Logistics: Managing multiple intermediaries can complicate logistics and inventory management, potentially leading to inefficiencies, miscommunication, and stockouts or overstock situations.    Loss of Product Control: Producers may have less control over how their products are marketed, priced, and presented to consumers. This can impact brand image and customer experience if intermediaries do not align with the producer's standards.    Quality and Service Concerns: The quality of service provided by middlemen can vary, and producers might not have direct oversight over customer service, product handling, or delivery, potentially leading to dissatisfied customers.","marks":"9","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>5>a>i","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"LABOUR MARKET AND UNEMPLOYMENT : INTRODUCTION","question":"Explain the concept:    -labour force","images":[],"marking_scheme":"The concept of the labour force refers to the total number of people who are actively employed or actively seeking employment. It includes all individuals who are of working age, capable of working, and either currently working (employed) or looking for work (unemployed).","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>5>a>ii","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"POPULATION : OVER POPULATION, UNDER POPULATION","question":"Explain the concept:  - over population","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Overpopulation is a concept that refers to a situation where the number of people in a particular area exceeds the capacity of the environment to support them with adequate resources and services. It occurs when the population size is too large relative to the available resources such as food, water, shelter, and employment opportunities, leading to negative consequences for both the environment and the quality of life for the inhabitants.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>5>a>iii","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"","topic":"LABOUR MARKET AND UNEMPLOYMENT : INTRODUCTION","question":"Explain the concept:  -mobility of labour","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Mobility of labour refers to the ability and willingness of workers to move between different jobs, occupations, industries, or geographic locations. It is an essential concept in economics as it impacts the efficiency and flexibility of the labor market, influencing employment rates, wage levels, and economic growth. Labour mobility can be categorized into two main types: geographical mobility and occupational mobility.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>5>a>iv","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iv","group":"","topic":"POPULATION : THEORIES OF POPULATION","question":"Explain the concept:  - optimum population","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Optimum population is an economic concept that refers to the ideal number of people that can be supported by a given set of resources and technology in a manner that maximizes the well-being of individuals and the overall economic productivity of a society. This population size allows for the most efficient use of resources, ensuring sustainable economic growth and high standards of living without causing excessive environmental degradation or resource depletion.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>5>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"POPULATION : DETERMINANTS OF POPULATION SIZE","question":"Outline four factors responsible for the rapid growth in the population of a country","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Cultural and Religious Beliefs: In some cultures and religions, having many children is encouraged and seen as a sign of prosperity and blessing.    Lack of Family Planning: Limited access to family planning services and education can lead to higher birth rates as people have more children, either intentionally or unintentionally.    Early Marriages: Societies where people marry at a younger age often experience higher birth rates due to longer reproductive periods.    Advancements in Healthcare: Improvements in medical technology, healthcare services, and access to medicines can reduce mortality rates, particularly infant and child mortality, leading to population growth.    Improved Nutrition: Better nutrition and food security reduce malnutrition and associated diseases, contributing to longer life expectancy.    Sanitation and Public Health: Enhanced sanitation practices and public health measures, such as vaccination programs and clean water supply, can reduce the prevalence of diseases and improve overall health outcomes.    In-migration: High levels of immigration can lead to population growth, especially if migrants are of reproductive age and start families in the new country.    Economic Opportunities: Countries with better economic prospects and higher living standards often attract immigrants seeking improved quality of life and job opportunities.    Economic Incentives: In some agrarian economies, larger families may be seen as an economic asset, providing more labor for farming and other family enterprises.    Social Security Systems: In countries without comprehensive social security systems, people might have more children to ensure support in old age.    Government Policies: Pronatalist policies and incentives, such as tax benefits for larger families or direct financial support, can encourage higher birth rates.","marks":"12","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>6>a>i","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"INDUSTRY & INDUSTRIALISATION : INTRODUCTION","question":"In recent times, developing countries that are predominantly agriculture-oriented are searching for ways of diversifying their economies. Many of these countries strive to exploit the available solid mineral deposits in their land as a means of promoting industrialization. In view of the above statement.    define the term:    industrialization","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Industrialization is the process by which an economy is transformed from primarily agricultural to one based on the manufacturing of goods. This transformation involves the extensive reorganization of an economy for the purpose of manufacturing. It typically includes the development of factories, the mechanization of production, and the concentration of labor in urban areas. Industrialization leads to technological innovation, increased production capacity, and a shift from rural to urban lifestyles. It is a key factor in economic growth and development, as it increases efficiency, productivity, and the standard of living.","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>6>a>ii","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"MAJOR NATURAL RESOURCES : INTRODUCTION","question":"In recent times, developing countries that are predominantly agriculture-oriented are searching for ways of diversifying their economies. Many of these countries strive to exploit the available solid mineral deposits in their land as a means of promoting industrialization. In view of the above statement.    define the term:  mineral resources","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Mineral resources are naturally occurring substances found in the Earth's crust that are extracted and used for various economic and industrial purposes. These resources are valuable due to their physical and chemical properties, which make them useful in a range of applications including construction, manufacturing, energy production, and technological development.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>6>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"MAJOR NATURAL RESOURCES : ONSHORE & OFFSHORE OF THE OIL SECTOR","question":"Apart from promoting industrialization, identify any three benefits of exploiting mineral deposits","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Increased National Income: Mineral extraction and processing contribute significantly to a country's GDP by adding value to raw materials and generating revenue through exports.    Government Revenue: Taxes, royalties, and licensing fees from mining operations provide substantial income for governments, which can be used for public services and infrastructure development.    Direct Employment: Mining operations create jobs in various roles, including extraction, processing, and administration, providing income for local communities.    Indirect Employment: The mining sector also supports indirect jobs in sectors such as transportation, logistics, equipment manufacturing, and service industries, boosting overall employment.    Improved Facilities: Mining projects often lead to the development of infrastructure, such as roads, railways, and ports, which can benefit local communities and facilitate economic activities.    Enhanced Services: Investments in infrastructure for mining can improve access to essential services such as healthcare, education, and utilities, enhancing the quality of life in mining regions.","marks":"6","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>6>c","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"","topic":"INDUSTRY & INDUSTRIALISATION : INTRODUCTION","question":"Outline any three benefits of industrialization to a developing country","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Increased GDP: Industrialization boosts the Gross Domestic Product (GDP) by expanding the manufacturing sector, which contributes significantly to national income.    Economic Diversification: It reduces dependency on agriculture and introduces new industries, creating a more balanced and resilient economy.    Employment Opportunities: The establishment of factories and industries generates numerous job opportunities, reducing unemployment and improving livelihoods.    Skill Development: Industrialization often involves training and upskilling workers, enhancing their expertise and contributing to human capital development.    Enhanced Infrastructure: Industrialization drives the development of essential infrastructure such as transportation networks (roads, railways, ports), utilities (electricity, water), and communication systems.    Urbanization: It leads to the growth of urban areas, improving access to services and amenities and fostering economic activities.","marks":"9","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>7>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"FINANCIAL INSTITUTION : CENTRAL BANK","question":"Define Central Bank","images":[],"marking_scheme":"A central bank is a national institution responsible for managing a country's currency, money supply, and interest rates. It plays a crucial role in the economic and financial stability of a country by implementing monetary policy and overseeing the banking system. Central banks are typically government-owned or operated and have a range of functions aimed at ensuring economic stability and growth.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>7>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"FINANCIAL INSTITUTION : CENTRAL BANK","question":"Outline three ways in which the Central Bank of a country can reduce money supply","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Policy Rate Adjustment: By raising the policy interest rates (such as the repo rate), the central bank makes borrowing more expensive and saving more attractive. This discourages excessive borrowing and spending by businesses and consumers, leading to a reduction in the money supply.    Open Market Operations (OMO): The central bank can sell government bonds or other securities in the open market. When investors purchase these securities, they pay the central bank, which withdraws money from circulation. This reduces the amount of money available in the economy.    Reserve Ratio Adjustment: The central bank can raise the reserve requirements for commercial banks, which is the percentage of deposits that banks must hold in reserve and not lend out. Higher reserve requirements reduce the amount of money available for lending, thus decreasing the money supply.","marks":"9","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>7>c>i","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"FINANCIAL INSTITUTION : CENTRAL BANK","question":"Explain how Central Bank plays its role as:    banker to the government","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Treasury Accounts: The Central Bank maintains the government's accounts, including its primary operating account. This allows for efficient management of government revenue and expenditures, ensuring that funds are available for various public services and obligations.    Transaction Processing: It processes payments and receipts on behalf of the government, such as tax collections, public sector salaries, and other government expenses.    Issuance and Redemption: The Central Bank often handles the issuance and redemption of government securities (bonds, treasury bills) used to finance government expenditures and manage public debt.    Debt Servicing: It assists in managing the servicing of public debt by scheduling interest payments and ensuring timely repayment of principal amounts.    Payments System: It provides a secure and efficient payments system for government transactions, facilitating transfers between government entities and ensuring smooth financial operations.    Cash Management: The Central Bank helps the government manage its cash flow, including short-term borrowing needs and liquidity requirements.    Economic Advice: It offers advice on monetary and fiscal policy, helping the government to make informed decisions regarding economic policy and financial management.    Financial Stability: By managing the government's accounts and securities, the Central Bank contributes to the overall financial stability of the economy.","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>7>c>ii","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"FINANCIAL INSTITUTION : CENTRAL BANK","question":"Explain how Central Bank plays its role as:  banker to commercial banks","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Emergency Liquidity: The Central Bank provides emergency funding to commercial banks facing temporary liquidity shortages. This role helps prevent bank failures and maintains confidence in the banking system.    Overnight Loans: It offers short-term loans to banks at a penalty rate, known as the discount rate or repo rate, to help them meet their immediate funding needs.    Compliance Monitoring: The Central Bank regulates and supervises commercial banks to ensure they comply with financial regulations and maintain sound practices. This includes setting prudential norms like capital adequacy requirements and liquidity ratios.    Risk Assessment: It conducts regular inspections and assessments to monitor the health of banks, mitigating systemic risks and protecting depositors' interests.    Payment Systems: The Central Bank operates and oversees payment systems that facilitate the transfer of funds between commercial banks. This includes systems for clearing checks and electronic payments, ensuring smooth and secure financial transactions.    Interbank Transactions: It manages interbank transactions, which involve the transfer of funds between banks, to maintain efficiency and stability in the financial system.    Reserve Accounts: Commercial banks are required to hold a certain percentage of their deposits as reserves with the Central Bank. The Central Bank manages these reserve accounts and ensures that banks comply with reserve requirements.    Interest on Reserves: The Central Bank may pay interest on reserves held by commercial banks, influencing their lending behavior and overall monetary conditions.    Open Market Operations: The Central Bank conducts open market operations, buying and selling government securities, to influence the money supply and interest rates. This affects the liquidity available to commercial banks and their lending activities.","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>7>c>iii","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"","topic":"FINANCIAL INSTITUTION : CENTRAL BANK","question":"Explain how Central Bank plays its role as:  lender of last resort","images":[],"marking_scheme":"As the lender of last resort, the Central Bank provides emergency funding to banks facing liquidity crises to prevent bank failures and maintain financial stability. It offers short-term loans and access to liquidity facilities to help banks meet immediate obligations. By doing so, it prevents systemic risk, stabilizes the financial system during times of stress, and preserves confidence in the banking sector. The Central Bank may impose higher interest rates and require collateral to manage risk and discourage reliance on emergency support.","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>8>a","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"ECONOMIC GROWTH AND DEVELOPMENT : INTRODUCTION","question":"Define economic development","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Economic development is the process through which a country or region improves the economic, social, and institutional conditions of its population.","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>8>b","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"ECONOMIC GROWTH AND DEVELOPMENT : INDICATORS OF GROWTH & DEVELOPMENT","question":"Highlight any three characteristics of a developing nations","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Income Per Capita: Developing nations typically have lower income per capita compared to developed countries, often reflecting widespread poverty and limited economic resources.    Basic Services: There is usually inadequate infrastructure, such as poor transportation, limited access to healthcare, and insufficient educational facilities, which hampers economic growth and quality of life.    Economic Structure: Many developing nations rely heavily on agriculture as the primary sector of their economy, with a significant portion of the population engaged in farming and related activities, often with low productivity and limited diversification.","marks":"9","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Economics>2024>8>c","subject":"Economics","year":"2024","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"","topic":"ECONOMIC GROWTH AND DEVELOPMENT : DEVELOPMENT PLANNING","question":"Explain any three measures a country can adopt to facilitates economic development","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Development of Physical Infrastructure: Building and upgrading infrastructure such as roads, ports, energy supply, and communication networks enhances connectivity and efficiency. Improved infrastructure supports business activities, reduces transaction costs, and attracts both domestic and foreign investment.    Social Infrastructure: Investing in healthcare, education, and housing improves living standards and boosts human capital, leading to a more skilled and healthier workforce.    Educational Programs: Expanding access to quality education and vocational training equips individuals with the skills needed for a modern economy. Higher educational attainment leads to increased productivity and innovation.    Skill Development Initiatives: Implementing programs that focus on specific skills and competencies relevant to various industries helps align the workforce with market needs and reduces unemployment.    Incentives for Investment: Offering tax incentives, subsidies, and favorable regulations can attract both domestic and foreign investors. Creating a conducive business environment fosters entrepreneurship and the growth of small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs).    Support for Innovation: Investing in research and development (R&D) and supporting technology startups drive innovation, enhance productivity, and create new economic opportunities.","marks":"9","difficulty":"2"}];